			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1632">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I&rsquo;m often at odds with <em>The Sun</em> politically, but it&rsquo;s the quality of the writing that matters. Jean Braithwaite&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/248/">Three Kims</a>&rdquo; [March 2006] was so good that I found myself reading it again, as if hoping to find in her deceptively simple style some sort of magic key. Like all good writers, she&rsquo;s a kind of Rumpelstiltskin, spinning pure gold out of the straw of everyday life.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Al Neipris<br>Mansfield, Massachusetts</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1633">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Jean Braithwaite&rsquo;s &ldquo;Three Kims&rdquo; reminded me of my own struggle with perfectionism. Convinced that I was being &ldquo;realistic,&rdquo; I habitually criticized myself and others, and viewed the world as random, meaningless, and punctuated by cruelty. Suffice it to say, it was a lonely existence.</p>

<p>Luckily the following books helped change my outlook: <em>The Joy of Imperfection</em> by Enid Howarth and Jan Tras, <em>Too Perfect</em> by Allan E. Mallinger and Jeannette DeWyze, and <em>The Highly Sensitive Person</em> by Elaine N. Aron. Now I do my best to be compassionate toward myself and others, and I remind myself every day that existence is wonderful.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Timothy Moore<br>Los Angeles, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1634">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>In &ldquo;Three Kims&rdquo; Jean Braithwaite refuses to encourage her partner, Helen, to write because of the odds against success. Couldn&rsquo;t she have warned Helen of the difficulty of getting published, yet encouraged her anyway? At the age of sixty-four I know my odds against getting published in a national publication grow longer each day, but I don&rsquo;t regret for a minute the time and effort I have put into writing.</p>

<p>Braithwaite also talks of Sharon, the English-department secretary, and wonders whether her position is &ldquo;as good as she can ever do.&rdquo; Perhaps it is as good as she needs to do because of everything else in her life. Are there no values beyond the trappings of success? Braithwaite&rsquo;s hard-boiled rationalism comes dangerously close to small-mindedness.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Coyd Walker<br>Scottsbluff, Nebraska</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
